title: Sources
text:
The data utilized in this analysis was originally sourced from Kaggle, which provided a comprehensive dataset detailing various aspects of Olympic athletes for the past 120 years.. To make the data more relevant and insightful, it underwent a thorough cleaning process. This involved refining the dataset to focus specifically on key attributes: ID, Sport, and Team. Additionally, the dataset was modified to include aggregated statistics such as Total Medals won by each athlete and the number of Olympics they attended.
The cleaning and modification steps aimed to enhance the clarity and usability of the data for further analysis. By emphasizing these specific attributes, the dataset now offers a clearer perspective on the athletes’ achievements and their Olympic careers. This approach not only streamlines the information but also provides a more focused view of the athletes’ performance across multiple Olympic Games

title: Models
text:
In this analysis, we employ a Bayesian generalized linear model to explore the relationship between the number of Olympics attended by athletes and the total number of medals they have won. The model is specified as follows: \[
\text{Olympics\_Attended} \sim \text{Poisson}(\lambda)
\]
Where the log of the expected value of the Poisson distribution is modeled as:
$$ \log(\lambda) = \beta_0 + \beta_1 \times \text{Total\_Medals} + \text{Sport}_{i} + \text{Team}_{j} $$
In the formula:

Olympis_Attended is the dependent variable (the number of Olympics attended).
Total_Medals is the predictor variable (the total number of medals won).
Sport and Team are random effects for the sport and team, respectively.




The model was fit using the brms package, and the following summarizes the key findings from the analysis:

**Intercept: Represents the baseline log-rate of the number of Olympics attended when the total number of medals is zero.
**Total Medals: Indicates how the log-rate of the number of Olympics attended changes with each additional medal won.
Random Effects: Include variations attributed to different sports and teams.


 Family: poisson 
  Links: mu = log 
Formula: Olympics_Attended ~ Total_Medals + (1 | Sport) + (1 | Team) 
   Data: smaller_athlete_data (Number of observations: 1408) 
  Draws: 4 chains, each with iter = 2000; warmup = 1000; thin = 1;
         total post-warmup draws = 4000

Multilevel Hyperparameters:
~Sport (Number of levels: 55) 
              Estimate Est.Error l-95% CI u-95% CI Rhat Bulk_ESS Tail_ESS
sd(Intercept)     0.03      0.02     0.00     0.08 1.00     2343     1858

~Team (Number of levels: 200) 
              Estimate Est.Error l-95% CI u-95% CI Rhat Bulk_ESS Tail_ESS
sd(Intercept)     0.02      0.02     0.00     0.07 1.00     2950     2016

Regression Coefficients:
             Estimate Est.Error l-95% CI u-95% CI Rhat Bulk_ESS Tail_ESS
Intercept        0.24      0.03     0.19     0.30 1.00     4969     2841
Total_Medals     0.18      0.02     0.14     0.21 1.00     6870     2794

Draws were sampled using sampling(NUTS). For each parameter, Bulk_ESS
and Tail_ESS are effective sample size measures, and Rhat is the potential
scale reduction factor on split chains (at convergence, Rhat = 1).
